data.content:
**No Thread.Abort migration is needed here.**

Your code uses only `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep` — none of which are affected by the .NET Framework → .NET 8 migration. These APIs work identically in modern .NET. There are no calls to `Thread.Abort`, `Thread.ResetAbort`, `Thread.Interrupt`, and no `ThreadAbortException` catch blocks.

This code will compile and run correctly as-is on .NET 8.

---

**Optional modernization** (unrelated to Thread.Abort migration): you could simplify this with `Parallel.ForEach` or `Task.Run`, e.g.:

```csharp
Parallel.ForEach(items, item =>
{
    Thread.Sleep(100);
    item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
});
```

This is purely a code-quality improvement — not a migration requirement.
